# Regression Testing Rules [MANDATORY ENFORCEMENT]

## Core Testing Principles

1. ALL tests MUST be executed after ANY code change.
2. Test results MUST be documented and reviewed before merging code.
3. NO code can be merged that causes test failures.
4. The development team is RESPONSIBLE for executing all tests.
5. The Executive Secretary (ES) MUST verify that ALL tests have been run.

## Acceptance Criteria Validation [CRITICAL]

For ALL user stories, the following procedure MUST be followed:

1. Each acceptance criterion MUST have corresponding test implementation
2. Tests MUST use the GIVEN-WHEN-THEN format to match acceptance criteria
3. Tests MUST be placed in the correct directory structure:
   - `/tests/acceptance/US-{ID}/` for acceptance tests
   - `/tests/unit/US-{ID}/` for unit tests
   - `/tests/integration/US-{ID}/` for integration tests
4. Each test file MUST be named according to the feature it tests:
   - `test_{feature}.js` for JavaScript tests
   - `test_{feature}.php` for PHP tests
   - `{feature}.feature` for Behat/Cucumber tests

## User Story Testing Process [MANDATORY]

When validating user stories against acceptance criteria:

1. ES MUST coordinate with SET to identify all user stories requiring testing
2. SET MUST verify each acceptance criterion has corresponding test implementation
3. SET MUST run all tests corresponding to the user story:
   ```bash
   # For specific user story testing
   npm run test:acceptance -- --story=US-{ID}
   npm run test:unit -- --story=US-{ID}
   npm run test:integration -- --story=US-{ID}
   ```
4. ES MUST review test results and verify ALL acceptance criteria pass
5. Any failed tests MUST be documented with:
   - Which acceptance criterion failed
   - Description of the failure
   - Impact on user story completion
   - Required actions to fix

## Test Result Documentation [REQUIRED]

Test results MUST be documented in the following format:

```
User Story: US-{ID}
Date: YYYY-MM-DD
Tester: [Name]

Acceptance Criteria Status:
1. [Criterion 1]: PASS/FAIL
   - Test file: path/to/test-file
   - Notes: [Any observations]

2. [Criterion 2]: PASS/FAIL
   - Test file: path/to/test-file
   - Notes: [Any observations]

Overall Status: PASS/FAIL
Required Actions: [List of actions if any tests failed]
```

## Sprint Acceptance Testing [CRITICAL]

Before closing any Sprint:

1. ES MUST verify ALL user stories have test coverage for EVERY acceptance criterion
2. SET MUST run the full test suite:
   ```bash
   npm run test:all
   ```
3. ES MUST review test results and identify any failures
4. Any failed tests MUST block Sprint closure until resolved
5. ES MUST provide a complete Sprint test report covering all user stories

## Test Coverage Requirements

1. Unit tests: Minimum 80% code coverage
2. Integration tests: All critical paths tested
3. Acceptance tests: 100% of acceptance criteria covered

## PHPCS Test Requirements [MANDATORY]

1. ALL code MUST pass PHPCS tests before being considered complete
2. PHPCS MUST be run with appropriate exclusions as defined in code-quality-standards.mdc
3. ES and SET MUST verify PHPCS tests pass for all user story implementations
4. PHPCS errors MUST be fixed BEFORE acceptance criteria are considered met

## Failure Response Protocol [REQUIRED]

When tests fail:

1. ES MUST immediately notify all relevant team members
2. SET MUST prioritize fixing test failures over new development
3. ES MUST track all test failures until resolved
4. After fixes, ALL tests must be rerun to verify no regressions
5. ES MUST document the resolution process

## Enforcement Guidelines

1. These rules are NON-NEGOTIABLE and MUST be followed for ALL development work
2. ES has AUTHORITY to block any merge or deployment that violates these rules
3. ANY exception to these rules requires documented approval
4. ALL team members are responsible for adherence to these rules

## User Story Sign-Off Process [MANDATORY]

1. No user story can be marked as complete without:
   - Passing ALL tests related to acceptance criteria
   - Passing ALL PHPCS tests
   - Complete test documentation
   - ES verification and sign-off

2. ES MUST verify completion using this checklist:
   - [ ] All acceptance criteria have test implementations
   - [ ] All tests pass successfully
   - [ ] PHPCS tests pass with no errors
   - [ ] Test documentation is complete
   - [ ] Performance metrics meet requirements

3. If ANY item fails, the user story CANNOT be considered complete

## Purpose
Ensure that all user stories, including those from previous sprints, continue to pass unit testing and behavior testing as new features are developed. This rule enforces a combined testing process (TDD with PHPUnit, BDD with Behat) to maintain software quality and prevent regressions.

## Core Principle [NON-NEGOTIABLE]
**The development team is solely responsible for executing all tests after every code change.**
- This responsibility is never passed to the user
- Tests must be run proactively without being asked
- Every code change requires full regression testing
- No exceptions or delays are permitted

## Process
1. **Behavior-Driven Development (BDD) with Behat**
   - Write feature files using Gherkin syntax (`.feature`) based on User Stories and Acceptance Criteria.
   - These feature files describe system behavior in natural language (Given/When/Then).
   - Implement step definitions in PHP to map Gherkin steps to executable code that interacts with the application.
   - Run Behat tests to verify acceptance criteria are met.

2. **Test-Driven Development (TDD) with PHPUnit**
   - Write failing unit tests with PHPUnit before writing implementation code.
   - Implement the minimum code required to make the unit tests pass.
   - Refactor code while ensuring all unit tests continue to pass.

3. **Regression Testing [MANDATORY AFTER ALL CHANGES]**
   - **REQUIRED TIMING**: Execute full test suite after EVERY code change
   - **SCOPE**: Run ALL tests (not just tests for new feature)
   - **RESPONSIBILITY**: Software Engineering Team (SET) MUST execute tests automatically
   - **PROACTIVE EXECUTION**: Tests are run without being prompted or requested
   - **REPORTING**: Test results must be reported clearly after each execution

4. **Automated Testing Pipeline**
   - Integrate both Behat (BDD) and PHPUnit (TDD) tests into the CI/CD pipeline.
   - All tests (Behat scenarios and PHPUnit tests) must run automatically on every commit.
   - Test suites should cover all user stories, current and previous.
   - Any test failures (Behat or PHPUnit) must block the build/deployment and be addressed immediately.

5. **Test Coverage**
   - Aim for 100% acceptance criteria coverage with Behat scenarios.
   - Maintain high unit test coverage (e.g., >80%) with PHPUnit.
   - Regularly review test coverage reports (PHPUnit coverage, Behat scenario results).
   - Track which tests verify which acceptance criteria.

6. **Results Documentation [REQUIRED]**
   - Document test execution results after every code change
   - Include timestamp of test execution
   - List all tests executed and their pass/fail status
   - Document coverage of acceptance criteria
   - Flag any failures or concerns immediately
   - Include test execution in every implementation report

## Test Execution Sequence [MUST FOLLOW]
After ANY code change:
1. Run new feature-specific unit tests
2. Run new feature-specific Behat tests
3. Run the ENTIRE test suite (all previous unit tests)
4. Run ALL Behat feature tests (including from previous sprints)
5. Document test results in standardized format
6. Report any failures immediately and fix before proceeding

## Tools
- **BDD**: Behat (using Gherkin syntax)
- **TDD**: PHPUnit
- **Automation**: CI/CD pipeline (e.g., GitHub Actions, Jenkins)

## Role Responsibilities [STRICT ENFORCEMENT]

### Executive Secretary (ES)
- Ensure regression testing process is followed after every change
- Verify SET has executed and reported test results
- Block further development if tests are not executed
- Maintain testing documentation requirements
- Confirm all test results are communicated clearly

### Software Engineering Team (SET)
- Execute ALL tests after EVERY code change without exception
- Report test results proactively without being prompted
- Fix any failing tests before moving to new development
- Maintain test infrastructure and ensure tests are reliable
- Never delegate testing responsibility to the user
- Document test execution results in standardized format

### Copy/Technical Writer (CTW)
- Write/refine feature files (Gherkin)
- Update documentation based on test results
- Ensure acceptance criteria are properly tested
- Document testing processes and standards

## Testing Report Template [REQUIRED AFTER EVERY CHANGE]
```
## Test Execution Report

### Change Summary
- [Brief description of code changes made]

### Test Execution Details
- Timestamp: [Date and time tests were executed]
- Executor: [Name/role of person who ran the tests]

### Unit Tests
- New tests: [Number of new tests] - Pass: [x] Fail: [y]
- Regression tests: [Number of existing tests] - Pass: [x] Fail: [y]
- Coverage: [Percentage of code covered]

### BDD Tests
- New feature scenarios: [Number] - Pass: [x] Fail: [y]
- Regression scenarios: [Number] - Pass: [x] Fail: [y]
- Acceptance criteria coverage: [x]%

### Issues Found
- [List any test failures or issues]
- [Actions taken to address issues]

### Verification
- [ ] All new tests pass
- [ ] All regression tests pass
- [ ] All acceptance criteria covered
- [ ] No regressions introduced
```

## Review
- Regularly review Behat scenarios and PHPUnit tests for clarity and effectiveness.
- Use sprint retrospectives to improve the testing process.
- Ensure the team understands and follows both BDD and TDD practices.
- Periodically audit test execution compliance. 